[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/usa/m8_greyhound]
In 1941, the U.S. Army Command held a competition for a design of an armored car capable of accomplishing functions of both a scout car and a tank destroyer. The T17 six-wheeler of the Ford company was first announced as the winner, but the project was eventually rejected. At the second stage of the competition, vehicles of the Ford company (T22) and Chrysler company (T23) reached the finals. An improved model of the Ford company’s armored vehicle, the T22E2 under the designation of M8 Armored Car eventually entered the army service. The armored car was manufactured from March 1943 to April 1944, and a total of 8,500 vehicles were made. In addition, 3,500 M20 command cars were made. They had no turret in comparison to the base model. 
Regardless of the name Light Armored Car, it is more correct to classify the M8 as a medium vehicle.German eight-axle armored cars had a lower weight than the U.S. cars. In addition to the U.S. Armed Forces, the M8 Armored Car was used in the British army under the designation of Greyhound. By the time it appeared on the battlefield, the M8 Armored Car was no longer suitable for the role as a tank destroyer, but it performed quite well as a scout car. Moreover, its powerful armament enabled it to combat light armored enemy vehicles.

[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/rus/m3a1_halftrack_rus]
American sources indicate that 1158 armored halftracks were sent to the USSR by lend-lease program, including 342 M2, only 2 M3, 401 M5 and 413 M9. Russian sources say that USSR received 1200 armored halftracks, but only 118 of them were given to armor or motorized forces (they were distributed in 1942 between recon units and headquarters of tank corps and armies). All other such vehicles were sent to artillery units (mainly to AT artillery), where they were used for towing many types of guns, including 85mm 52K mod.1939 AA guns and 100mm BS-3 mod.1944 AT guns.

[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/ger/ba_64_ger]
Captured armored cars BA-64 were used in police units on occupied territories from 1941 to 1944. Some of them were used on the front line, for example SS division 'Das Reich' employed them during Kursk battle.

[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/rus/pzspw_p204f_rus]
Several french armored cars, which were issued to Wehrmacht after the fall of France, were captured in Russia in 1941-42 and were sent back to the front lines after repair.

[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/rus/sdkfz_251_1_ausf_c_rus]
Captured german armored halftracks were widely used by Red Army during entire war.

[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/ger/sdkfz_231]
Very low cross-country ability of heavy German six-wheeled armored cars Sd.Kfz.231 (6-rad) was the reason for developing heavy 8-wheeled (8-rad) armored car, which was designated Sd.Kfz.231 too. New chassis was designed by company Buessing-NAG and it’s mass production started in 1938 and continued until the end of the war. All eight wheels of this chassis were driving ones and were partially covered by armor. Unlike most German armored cars, powerful diesel engine Tatra 103 was used for this one, starting from 1943. This 12-cylinder V-like engine was capable of providing 210 h.p. and propelled the car (9-12 tons) to the maximum speed of 80km/h. Transmission consisted of double disk dry clutch, gear box with three forward speeds and three backward ones and demultiplicator. Powerful engine and 8-wheeled chassis allowed the car to get over 30° slopes, 0.5 meters high walls and fords up to 1.2 meters deep. Long polyhedral hull was composed of rolled armor sheets placed with straight and inverse inclinations. Like 6-wheeled cars, this one had two steering wheels, making retreat without turning the vehicle possible.
There were several modifications of this car : Sd.Kfz.231 8-rad – recon armored car with 20mm gun,  Sd.Kfz.232 8-rad — recon armored car with 20mm gun and frame radio antenna, Sd.Kfz.233 8-rad — recon armored car with 75mm L/24 howitzer (109 produced), Sd.Kfz.263 8-rad — radio car with frame radio antenna (240 poduced). Depending on modification, these heavy armored cars were used in heavy armored car companies of recon battalions of Panzer and motorized divisions, infantry support units, radio platoons of command units of all levels. It is worth to mention that 8-wheeled drive was revolutionary for that time and was developed further after the war. German industry produced over 1444 heavy 8-wheeled armored cars of all variants. 344 Sd.Kfz.231 8-rad were used in Wehrmacht combat units at the end off March 1945.

