Germans used captured T-60 and T-70 light tanks for transportation of infantry and light guns; their turrets were often removed.

[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/ger/sdkfz_251_10_ausf_c]
Platoon commander vehicle in motorized infantry units. Armament: 37mm anti-tank gun PaK-35/36 with stadard shield.


[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/ger/sdkfz_251_9_ausf_d]
SdKfz.251/9 was an armored car fitted with 75mm short-barreled KwK-37 L/24 (designated K-51 later), which was used on Pz.Kpfw.IV Ausf.A - F-1 tanks earlier. These armored cars were issued to grenadier units.
Front armor shape changed somewhat in comparison with a regular SdKfz.251 and the gun was protected by a small rectangular shield. Gun carriage was mounted on a pedestal fastened to the floor of the fighting compartment. Gun could be elevated from -10 to +12 degrees and rotated up to 12 degrees to each side. Telescopic sight SfiZF-1 was installed, ammo load consisted of 52 AP and HE shells.
SdKfz.251/9 weighed 8.53 tons fully laden, required 5 men crew, and carried one 7.92mm MG-42 machinegun in addition to main gun.
The prototype was made by Bussing - NAG during March 1942, and two of them were sent to East front at July 1942. These trials were successful and 150 such vehicles were ordered at the same month. German soldiers called them 'Stummel' (cigarette end) because of short gun barrel.

[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/ger/sdkfz_251_17_ausf_c]
SdKfz.251/17 was a self-propelled anti-aircraft gun (automatic 20mm Flak-38 AA). It weighed 8.8 tons and required 4 - 6 people crew. It's maximal height was 2.25 meters.
Total 211 units were made. First ones (using SdKfz.251 Ausf.A and В chassis) were tested at 26 October 1943. SdKfz.251 Ausf. C - based series were also produced. Near the end of the war production of new series started, equipped with 360-degrees gun mount.
Gun in late series vehicles was placed in a small turret. Sides were made foldable to maximize sector of fire.
These vehicles usually were issued to Luftwaffe (AA gun units), in addition, some tank units also had them.
 
[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/ger/sdkfz_251_22_ausf_d]
Lack of AT artillery forced Germans to create one more SdKfz.251-based armored car - 7,5-cm Pak.40 L/46 Mittlerer Schutzenpanzerwagen, equipped with 75mm Pak-40/1 AT gun. The gun was mounted in the same way like it was done on SdKfz.234/4 "Puma". Gun carriage was placed immediately behind the driver seat, part of the roof was removed to make room for gun suspension mechanism. Horizontal aiming angles were -20 degrees to the left and 18 degrees to the right, elevation angles were limited from -3 to +48 degrees. Ammunition load consisted of 22 shots (17 shells in container to the right of the gun and 5 in container below the gun). Gun crew consisted of 4 crewmen. Commander was located in the rear, while gunner sat on the collapsible wooden seat to the left of the gun, near the two loaders.
The armored car was too overloaded, which often caused chassis and front wheels failures. SdKfz.251/22 prototype was ready at 3 December 1944, mass production started during the same month. Panzer divisions "model 1945" should have had 9 SdKfz.251/22 in artillery batteries, 3 in recon battalions and 6 in tank units. Total 268 were produced.

[EncDescription_data/units/armoredcar/ger/sdkfz_251_23_ausf_d]
SdKfz.251/23 was armed with 20mm KwK-38 automatic gun and 7.92mm MG-42 machine gun set up in a Hangelaffete-28 turret (SdKfz.234/1, SdKfz.222 and Aufklaerungpanzer 38(t) had the same turret). Gun elevation could be adjusted from – 10 to + 85 degrees. This vehicle required 4-men crew. FuG-12 radio equipment was installed.
This was a final variant in SdKfz.251 series, SdKfz.251/23 used Ausf.D chassis. Mass production of SdKfz.251/23 started at December 1944.
